{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-5","id":"msg_01ANqcFMPjoN7BphwHibVAZE","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"This gives me a complete picture. Config is small enough that I don't need further grepping — no other file reads env vars directly (settings all flow through `Settings`/`load_config`).\n\n## Where settings live\n\n**`pyserver/config.py`** is the single source of truth:\n\n1. **`Settings`** (dataclass, line 8-16) — declares every tunable field with its default, e.g. `database_path`, `host`, `port`, `debug`, `webhook_url`.\n2. **`load_config(path=None)`** (line 19-29) — the only place environment variables are read. It currently supports exactly one env var, `TASKHUB_CONFIG`, which points to a JSON file. Precedence: explicit `path` arg > `TASKHUB_CONFIG` env var (as a file path) > dataclass defaults. Field-level overrides only happen if that JSON file sets them — there's no per-field env var support today.\n\nConsumers (`pyserver/app.py:create_app` at line 24-30, and `pyserver/cli.py:main` at line 8-12 via `run()` in `app.py:33-37`) never touch env vars directly — they just call `load_config()` and read attributes off the returned `Settings` instance.\n\n## Plan to add a new tunable env-overridable setting\n\nSay the new setting is `request_timeout: float = 30.0` (analogous pattern applies to any new field):\n\n1. **`pyserver/config.py` → `Settings`**: add the new field with its default, e.g. `request_timeout: float = 30.0`.\n2. **`pyserver/config.py` → `load_config`**: after building the `Settings` (whether from JSON or defaults), add an explicit env-var override, e.g.:\n   ```python\n   settings = Settings(**raw) if candidate and os.path.exists(candidate) else Settings()\n   if (env_val := os.environ.get(\"TASKHUB_REQUEST_TIMEOUT\")) is not None:\n       settings.request_timeout = float(env_val)\n   return settings\n   ```\n   (Since `Settings` is currently built and returned in two separate branches, this requires restructuring `load_config` to funnel both paths through one `settings` variable so the env override applies uniformly, or duplicating the override in both branches.)\n3. No other file needs to change — everything downstream (`App.__init__` in `pyserver/app.py:11`, and any route/service code) just reads `settings.<field>` off the object produced by `load_config`.\n\nIf per-field env overrides become a recurring need (not just this one setting), the cleaner long-term fix is a loop in `load_config` over `Settings.__dataclass_fields__` matching `TASKHUB_<FIELD_NAME upper>` env vars, rather than hand-adding an `if` per field — but for a single new setting, the explicit override above is the minimal, in-scope change."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":354,"cache_read_input_tokens":36060,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":354},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"a6daf048-b5c2-4021-aeaa-7ccaa4009f2e","uuid":"fb56621b-ab1e-407f-8e73-2a62fe12d448","request_id":"req_011CchLG8LmZS4twEE8XKdWE"}
